# **JSON Tasks API**

A small FastAPI app that stores tasks as JSON Lines (one JSON object per line) in tasks.txt. Each task has an auto-incrementing integer id (single-process), a title, and a boolean completed flag.


This README explains how to install, run and use the API, plus notes about storage and concurrency.



**Features**

* Create tasks with an auto-incrementing integer id
* Store tasks in JSON Lines format (tasks.txt)
* Load/save helpers that read/write the file as described

Endpoints:

GET / — root check

POST /tasks — create task (201)

GET /tasks — list tasks (optional ?completed=true|false filter)

GET /tasks/{task\_id} — get single task

PUT /tasks/{task\_id} — replace/update a task

DELETE /tasks/{task\_id} — delete one task (204)

DELETE /tasks — delete all tasks (204)


#### **Prerequisites**


Python 3.8+

pip

**Recommended virtual environment**:

*python -m venv .venv*

*source .venv/bin/activate   # Linux/macOS*

*.venv\\Scripts\\activate      # Windows PowerShell*



**Install dependencies**:

*pip install fastapi "uvicorn\[standard]"*


Place the FastAPI app file (e.g., main.py) in your project directory (the file contents are the implementation you were given). The file saves data to tasks.txt in the process working directory by default.


#### **Run the Server**


**Run with uvicorn**:

*uvicorn app:app --reload*


This starts the server on **http://127.0.0.1:8000** by default.


**Notes:**

The app uses an in-memory counter and tasks.txt for persistence. Do not run multiple worker processes (e.g., uvicorn --workers N) unless you add file locking or switch to a Database. Multiple processes will cause conflicting writes and inconsistent ids.

--reload is for development; it restarts the process on code changes.


**Interactive docs**

* Open the Swagger UI: **http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs**
* Open ReDoc: **http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc**

You can test the endpoints interactively there.


#### **API usage examples**

Use curl, http (HTTPie), or Python requests in an another terminal while the app is running.


**Create a task (POST /tasks):**

curl -X POST "http://127.0.0.1:8000/tasks" \\

&nbsp; -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\

&nbsp; -d '{"title":"Learn FastAPI","description":"Watch tutorial","completed":false}'


**Response (201):**

{"id":1,"title":"Learn FastAPI","description":"Watch tutorial","completed":false}


**List all tasks (GET /tasks):**

curl "http://127.0.0.1:8000/tasks"


**Filter by completion (GET /tasks?completed=true):**

curl "http://127.0.0.1:8000/tasks?completed=true"


**Get a single task (GET /tasks/{id}):**

curl "http://127.0.0.1:8000/tasks/1"


**Update (replace) a task (PUT /tasks/{id}):**

curl -X PUT "http://127.0.0.1:8000/tasks/1" \\

&nbsp; -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\

&nbsp; -d '{"title":"Learn HTTP", "description":"Watch Youtube", "completed":true}'


**Delete a task (DELETE /tasks/{id}):**

curl -X DELETE "http://127.0.0.1:8000/tasks/1"


**Response status:** 204 No Content


**Delete all tasks (DELETE /tasks):**

curl -X DELETE "http://127.0.0.1:8000/tasks"


**Response status:** 204 No Content


**Root check:**

curl http://127.0.0.1:8000/


**Response:** {"status":"ok","tasks\_file":"tasks.jsonl"}


#### **Data file (tasks.txt)**

File path: tasks.txt (in the process working directory, configurable in the code by changing DATA\_FILE)

Format: JSON Lines — each line is a single JSON object, e.g.:

{"id":1,"title":"Learn FastAPI","description":"Watch tutorial","completed":false}

{"id":2,"title":"Buy groceries","description":"Milk","completed":true}

{"id":3,"title":"Exercise","description":"30 min run","completed":false}


**The app provides:**

* load\_tasks() — returns \[] if file doesn't exist, otherwise reads each non-empty line, strips whitespace, parses JSON into a Python dict; invalid JSON lines are skipped and a warning is printed.
* save\_tasks(tasks) — overwrites the file and writes each task as a single JSON line (newline ensures each task is on its own line).


#### **Behavior \& concurrency notes**

The id is auto-incrementing and determined from in-memory state; when the server starts it initializes \_next\_id to max(existing id) + 1 or 1 if no tasks exist.

The app uses a threading.Lock to protect in-memory list and file writes. That makes it safe for concurrent requests in a single process (the typical uvicorn single-worker mode).

It is NOT safe across multiple processes/workers. If you run multiple workers, each worker has its own in-memory counter and lock, and concurrent writes will conflict and corrupt tasks.jsonl. To support multiple processes use:

A proper database (Postgres, SQLite with careful transaction use), or

Add file locking (e.g., portalocker) and robust conflict handling.


#### **Troubleshooting**

Connection refused: ensure uvicorn is running and you are pointing to the correct host/port.

IDs not incrementing as expected: check the startup output to ensure the app read existing tasks correctly. If you manually edited tasks.jsonl, ensure every line is valid JSON.

File corruption after concurrent writes: switch to a DB or add file locking.


#### **Example quick start**

* Save the app to main.py
* Run: **uvicorn app:app --reload**
* Open **http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs** and create a task via the User Interface or use the curl examples above.



